  "prompt": "What is the transpose of a matrix ?",
  "response": "The transpose of a matrix is a new matrix created by interchanging its rows and columns. Here are the key points about matrix transposition:\n\n1. Definition:\n- For a matrix A, its transpose is denoted as A^T\n- Each row of the original matrix becomes a column in the transposed matrix\n- The dimensions of the matrix are swapped\n\n2. Example:\nOriginal matrix A:\n[1 2 3]\n[4 5 6]\n\nTransposed matrix A^T:\n[1 4]\n[2 5]\n[3 6]\n\n3. Properties:\n- (A^T)^T = A\n- (A + B)^T = A^T + B^T\n- (kA)^T = k(A^T), where k is a scalar\n- (AB)^T = B^T A^T\n\n4. Special cases:\n- Square matrices can be transposed symmetrically\n- Symmetric matrices remain unchanged when transposed\n- Diagonal matrices remain the same when transposed\n\n5. Calculation:\n- Swap rows and columns\n- Maintain original matrix elements\n- Reverse row and column indices\n\nTransposition is useful in linear algebra, solving systems of equations, and various mathematical and computational applications.",
